Fortunate to have many dim sum choices in Chicago, noticed that Macau Tasty House has some interesting variations of your standard dimsum. Service was prompt and friendly (I did speak Canto with them). The mala siu mai was a yummy twist, if you’re feeling something different I recommend the preserved veg spare ribs rice roll. The bakery items are made in house!
Chinese food, very satisfying. Service is prompt even when they are busy. Really nothing but good experiences here. The place has a nice feel to it.
A fav spot for tasty Chinese food. Don't worry if it's busy, it is worth the wait. Certainly worth going back to.

Overall, relaxing on any day except holidays.

Came to visit Chicago for the first time, first stop, of course China town, after walking around, my GF and I asked the locals for advice where to dine, 7/10 recommended this place, so we decided to give it a try, let’s say it’s “a pearl in a haystack”, the appearance of this place is no different to a lower end type of Chinese restaurant, but I’m here for the food, we’ve order about 4 dishes, they’ve all came out to be 100% satisfying. Honestly better than a lot of places in Toronto. 5 stars for the food, 3 stars for the look, and 3 stars for the service.  Taste is what I was looking for the most, so I’ve given them a 5, if I want service, I’ll go to a star rated hotel restaurant and not china town.

Having a family dinner here.  Yummy eel rice, preorder home made soup, and the bean curd duck brought memories back to childhood.  Thank you for the precious refreshments of my childhood.   Would most definitely come often.  ❤️
Tasty food was reminiscent of hometown flavors ! Large portion and decent price. Good for family gathering.

Casual Chinese cuisine. Reasonable price. Special dishes from Macau, a blended  Portuguese and Chinese dishes. The Portuguese chicken was good. Lunch menu has variety. The place is old style Chinatown style.
